# Toy Example: Adaptive WNNM Image Fusion

This notebook demonstrates the core idea of adaptive singular value reweighting using a simple 4x4 synthetic example.

```python
import torch
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from awnnm_fusion import adaptive_wnnm_fusion

# Create synthetic complementary patterns
I1 = torch.tensor([
    [100, 100, 50, 50],
    [100, 100, 50, 50],
    [50,  50,  0,  0],
    [50,  50,  0,  0]
], dtype=torch.float32) / 100.0

I2 = torch.tensor([
    [0,   0,  50,  50],
    [0,   0,  50,  50],
    [50, 50, 100, 100],
    [50, 50, 100, 100]
], dtype=torch.float32) / 100.0

# Perform fusion
fused = adaptive_wnnm_fusion(I1, I2, lambda_reg=0.055, max_iter=10)

# Plot results
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(12, 4))
axes[0].imshow(I1, cmap='gray'); axes[0].set_title('I1')
axes[1].imshow(I2, cmap='gray'); axes[1].set_title('I2')
axes[2].imshow(fused, cmap='gray'); axes[2].set_title('Fused (AWNNM)')

plt.suptitle('Toy 4x4 Fusion Example')
plt.show()

print("Fused image shape:", fused.shape)
